  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering in various jurisdictions around the world. Here are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Investigative Procedures**:\n   - Federal Investigative Guidelines (FBI)\n   - Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n   - Counter-terrorism and Financial Intelligence (CFI)\n\n2. **Prosecutorial Procedures**:\n   - **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**: Enacted in 1970, the BSA requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering.\n   - **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**: This Act made money laundering a federal crime and established specific penalties.\n   - **Patriot Act (2001)**: Enhanced the BSA by imposing additional anti-money laundering (AML) requirements on financial institutions.\n   - **FinCEN Regulations**: The Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) issues regulations under the BSA to combat money laundering and other financial crimes.\n\n### European Union\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**:\n   - **1st AMLD (1991)**: Established the initial framework for combating money laundering.\n   - **2nd AMLD (2001)**: Expanded the scope and included additional sectors.\n   - **3rd AMLD (2005)**: Aligned with FATF recommendations and introduced stricter customer due diligence measures.\n   - **4th AMLD (2015)**: Further strengthened the AML framework and introduced beneficial ownership registries.\n   - **5th AMLD (2018)**: Enhanced transparency and extended AML requirements to virtual currency exchanges and custodian wallet providers.\n   - **6th AMLD (2020)**: Introduced stricter criminal liability and harmonized the definition of money laundering across member states.\n\n### United Kingdom\n1. **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**: Defines money laundering offenses and outlines procedures for confiscation and recovery of proceeds of crime.\n2. **Money Laundering Regulations**: These regulations transpose EU AML directives into UK law and set out requirements for businesses to prevent money laundering.\n3. **Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Act 2018**: Provides the legal framework for imposing financial sanctions and enhancing AML measures.\n\n### International\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: An intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. FATF\u2019s recommendations are adopted by many countries globally.\n2. **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, it includes provisions for combating money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Known as the Palermo Convention, it includes measures to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\nThese statutes and regulations provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities. They impose various obligations on financial institutions and other entities to report suspicious activities, conduct due diligence, and maintain records.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
